The Anatomy of a Goodreads Book Rating¶

Authors: dela Resma, Ginez, Inocencio, Nepomuceno, Piquero, Punzalan of LT8

Executive Summary¶


There was a time when everyone was reading Harry Potter because of its movie adaptation and word of mouth recommendations. After this surge in book and movie reviews, Harry Potter’s book sales significantly increased. We can say that these reviews encourage new Harry Potter fans to read the books. But how about good books with no movie adaptations or sudden increase in popularity?

This is how Goodreads can unearth these hidden gems. Goodreads is an American social cataloging website that allows individuals to search its database of books, annotations, quotes, and reviews. Users can sign up and register books to generate library catalog, reading lists and create their own groups of book suggestions, surveys, polls, blogs, and discussions. The company is owned by the online retailer Amazon, with offices located in San Francisco.

Goodreads is the leading book review website trusted by millions of users worldwide. In this project, our group analyzed the different book features and their relationship with book ratings. This was done using various data mining, wrangling, and visualization techniques. Results show that the most likely predictors for book rating are the number of book pages and the number of ratings. Insights on the other feature interactions also emerged. It was found that e-books are more prevalent for the romance genre and scarce for children’s books and comics. Further, faster reading time is observed for the e-book format. The data also validated the common notion that reading time is longer for books with higher number of pages and that there is a higher occurrence of text reviews compared to non-text.

Since there are limited book features in the dataset, it is recommended in future studies to extract user profiles as well, such as their age, gender, and other demographic and psychometric information of the reviewers. As for the current dataset available, it would be better to perform the methodology on a larger portion of the database to validate this study and gain more accurate information. Machine learning algorithms could also be explored.

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Problem Statement

1. Introduction¶


Goodreads was launched in 2007 and has since been the go-to site for book lovers and readers alike for reviews and recommendations. Through this website, you can:
  • See what books your friends' bookshelves and vice versa
  • Track the books you're reading, have read, and want to read
  • Check out personalized book recommendations
  • Find out if a book is a good fit for you


Otis Chandler, co-founder of Goodreads, came up with the website idea while scanning his friend's bookshelf for ideas on what book he should read next. He realized that he wanted recommendations from a friend rather than strangers and bestseller lists. Together with his now wife, Elizabeth Otis, who is also a co-founder, they created a website where people can explore their friends' shelves and what they thought of the books.
In late 2017, Mengting Wan, et al., students from the University of California, San Diego (UCSD) performed web-scraping Goodreads' users public shelves that everyone can see on the web without needing to login into Goodreads. Three groups of datasets were collected:
  • meta-data of the books
  • user-book interactions (users' public shelves)
  • users' detailed book reviews

Since Goodreads is considered a home for book lovers and primary book recommender for a person's next purchase, our group aims to understand the factors that can affect a user's rating on a certain book.

2. Problem Statement¶


Goodreads is a haven for book lovers who share reviews and recommendations to others. The site intends to promote a culture of reading and create curiosity in books by publicizing which books their members have read or have interests in. Our group aims to discover how these book lovers rate each book and determine which features/factors that drive ratings up. We also want to find out which book features are related to each other. By exploring the data set from Goodreads, we hope that our insights will shed light on which book features should book readers and even authors consider reading or writing in the future. In doing this, our group hopes to help in building a culture of reading books.

3. Data Description¶


From the twenty-two datasets found in the UCSD Book Graph dataset collection, we selected twelve datasets that allowed us to segment the books and interactions per genre. The book dataset per genre provided information on each book like the title and publication year of each book. On the other hand, the interactions dataset per genre provided the engagement of each user for every book like the date and time when the user started reading.

After selecting the relevant columns in each of the datasets, we dropped the rows with null values and formatted date and time columns. In order to determine the genre of each book, we added a genre column in the books datasets. The main dataframe was formed by merging `goodreads_books` per genre dataset to `goodreads_interactions` per genre dataset using `book_id` to map the data. Once the books and interactions datasets per genre were merged, we took a sample and appended it to the main dataframe and was saved as a CSV file. As a result, we were able to form 30,000 rows and 13 columns in the main dataframe. The table below contains information about each column:


Table 3.1 Book Feature Information
Feature Data Type Description
book_id int64 Unique identifier per book
is_ebook bool Form of reading material (e.g. book, e-book)
text_reviews_count int64 Total number of text reviews per book
average_rating float64 Raw rating per book from book per genre dataset
language_code object Language of book
num_pages float64 Total number of pages in the book
publication_month float64 Month of publication per book
publication_year float64 Year of publication per book
ratings_count int64 Total number of users who rated a book
title object Given title of the book
sample_rating float64 Calculated rating based on the interaction per genre sample size
read_duration float64 Calculated average reading time per book per genre sample size
genre object Genre of the book (e.g. fantasy_paranormal, romance)

4.1 DATA MINING and WRANGLING¶

4.1.1 Choosing appropriate data sources¶

Book genres were chosen using the following criteria:

  • Has both books and interactions JSON files available.
  • Has at least 1 million rows in the interactions JSON file.


These criteria were chosen to enable equal and enough sampling of data when these genres are merged into one pandas DataFrame. The genres to be analyzed are - fantasy/paranormal, comics, young adult, history and biography, romance and children. The mystery/thriller and poetry genres were excluded since they did not meet our chosen criteria.

4.1.2 Filtering columns and rows¶


For each of the genres selected, the following cleaning and manipulation steps were performed on the respective books JSON file:

  • Read first N rows of JSON file where N was manually chosen for each genre such that enough data is available, while avoiding overloading of the server (suggestion: instances of DataFrame building failure). Store in pandas DataFrame named df_books.



Table 4.1 Number of rows read from each genre.
Genre N rows extracted
Fantasy/Paranormal 100,000
Comics 80,000
Young Adult 90,000
History and Biography 100,000
Romance 100,000
Children 100,000


  • Remove rows with rating count < 500. This value was set to ensure only well-reviewed books are included in the analysis.
  • Unnecessary columns were removed.
  • Afterwards, a list of book IDs present in df_books was generated. This will be used in the cleaning of the interactions dataset.

Likewise, each of the interactions JSON files were also subject to the following operations:

  • Read first 1 million rows of JSON file and store in a pandas DataFrame named df_interact. This limitation was made to avoid overloading the server as there are multiple genres.
  • Unnecessary columns were removed.
  • Remove rows with book IDs not included in df_books to avoid null values and lessen computational resources needed in succeeding steps.
  • Remove rows that has an empty string value for read_at and started_at columns.

4.1.3 Merging data from df_books and df_interact¶

  • Convert read_at and started_at columns of df_interact to datetime type.
  • Create a new column read_duration in df_interact that contains reading duration in days. This value was determined from the difference of the read_at and started_at columns.
  • Calculate average rating and average reading duration each book ID in df_interact by using groupby function.
  • Insert average rating and average reading duration columns in df_books as, mapping based on book ID.
  • Drop rows in df_books that has a null value for both of the added columns or having negative value for reading duration.
  • Sample 5,000 rows from the remaining rows of df_books.
  • Add a column 'genre' to label the sampled rows before appending it to the Goodreads_Sampled.csv file, containing all the genre processed and updated in every loop.

Code for Generating Goodreads_Sampled.csv¶

In [ ]:
path1 = '/mnt/data/public/bookgraph/goodreads_books_'
path2 = '/mnt/data/public/bookgraph/goodreads_interactions_'

files = ['fantasy_paranormal.json.gz',
         'comics_graphic.json.gz',
         'young_adult.json.gz',
         'history_biography.json.gz',
         'romance.json.gz',
         'children.json.gz']

x = 0  # counter

book_nrows = [100_000, 80_000, 90_000, 100_000, 100_000, 100_000]

for file in files:
    df_books = pd.read_json(path1 + file, lines=True, nrows=book_nrows[x])
    df_interact = pd.read_json(path2 + file, lines=True, nrows=1_000_000)

    df_books = df_books[df_books['ratings_count'] > 500]

    # Useful columns for df_books
    cols = ['book_id',
            'is_ebook',
            'text_reviews_count',
            'average_rating',
            'language_code',
            'num_pages',
            'publication_month',
            'publication_year',
            'ratings_count',
            'title']

    df_books = df_books[cols]
    book_list = df_books['book_id'].tolist()

    # Useful columns for df_interact
    cols = ['user_id',
            'book_id',
            'review_id',
            'is_read',
            'rating',
            'date_added',
            'read_at',
            'started_at']
    df_interact = df_interact[cols]

    df_interact = df_interact[df_interact['book_id'].isin(book_list)]
    df_interact['is_read2'] = ((df_interact['started_at'].str.len() > 0) &
                               (df_interact['read_at'].str.len() > 0))
    df_interact = df_interact[df_interact['is_read2'] == True]

    df_interact['started_at'] = pd.to_datetime(df_interact['started_at'],
                                               utc=True)
    df_interact['read_at'] = pd.to_datetime(df_interact['read_at'],
                                            utc=True)
    df_interact['read_duration'] = ((df_interact['read_at'] -
                               df_interact['started_at']).dt.days)

    sample_rating = df_interact.groupby('book_id')['rating'].mean()

    df_books['sample_rating'] = df_books['book_id'].map(sample_rating)
    df_books = df_books[df_books.sample_rating > 0]
    df_books.dropna(subset=['sample_rating'], inplace=True)

    sample_duration = df_interact.groupby('book_id')['read_duration'].mean()

    df_books['read_duration'] = df_books['book_id'].map(sample_duration)
    df_books = df_books[df_books.read_duration >= 0]
    df_books.dropna(subset=['read_duration'], inplace=True)

    df_books['genre'] = file.split('.')[0]
    df_books = df_books.sample(5000, random_state=42)

    if x == 0:
        df_books.to_csv('Goodreads_Sampled.csv',
                        mode='w',
                        header=True,
                        index=False)
    else:
        df_books.to_csv('Goodreads_Sampled.csv',
                        mode='a',
                        header=False,
                        index=False)
    del df_books
    del df_interact

    x += 1

4.1.4 Data Disclaimer¶

Note that since only the first 1 million rows are read from the interactions JSON file for each genre, there is a discrepancy with the population mean of the average rating (average_rating column) and the mean of the sampled rows (sample_rating column).

5. Results¶


The preceding chapter discussed the procedures and techniques needed to come up with the results. In this section, the interpretation of the data will be presented. First, rating related insights will be discussed whether or not it is affected by average duration and other book features. Next, non-rating related features will be inspected to see if a correlation to other features can be found. The discovered key takeaways will be discussed in this section.

5.1 Factors Affecting Book Rating¶


There are two main thoughts for rating-related results. First, the average rating vs. average duration will be examined to see if they have some kind of relationship as whole and per genre. Then, other features will be checked to see if they have connection to average rating. These features are rating count, text review count, number of pages, language, e-book, and publication date.

5.1.1 Average Rating vs. Average Reading Duration¶


Before proceeding to examining the relationship of average rating and average duration, let's look at the averages per genre.

From the bar chart above, history and biography books are the longest to read while comics and graphics are the fastest to read. This is due to the texts associated with them. Most comics/graphics have less words while history/biography books are verbose in nature.


The second bar chart indicates that there are small differences with average rating. This suggests that book genre may not affect the ratings of the book.


Now, let's see if average rating has an association with average duration. Below are the scatter plot and bar chart (in buckets) of average rating vs. average duration.

Figure 5.12 Language vs. Average Rating

The top 10 recorded languages (50 or more books) were observed versus their corresponding average ratings. Arabic books have the highest average rating while Indonesian books got the lowest average ratings.

# Generate Mean and Standard Deviation Columns for the Rating per genre
df_year['publication_year'] = pd.to_datetime(df_year['publication_year'],
                                             format='%Y')
df_year = df_year.set_index('publication_year')
df_year['roll_mean'] = df_year['average_rating'].rolling(10).mean()
df_year['roll_std'] = df_year['average_rating'].rolling(10).std()
df_year['upper_bound'] = df_year['roll_mean'] + 2*df_year['roll_std']

df_year = df_year.reset_index()

               size=0.5)

               size=0.5)

               title=None)

5.2.1 Book Format (E-Book)¶


The book format is not related to the number of pages and the average reading time. Meanwhile a higher number of ratings and text reviews can be associated more to hard copies. Most of the available e-books are also from a more recent publication year. This is expected because most of the older books are not available in a digital format.


It is interesting to note the differences in the percentage of book format distribution. The highest of which is the romance genre. This could be due to its target audience -- young to middle-aged adults, and the ease of access e-books give them. Another possible reason, is that e-books are more discreet and hence, more favored for the romance genre.


The genres with the lowest percentage of e-books are children's books and comics. This is also likely due to the target consumers of these books - toddlers, teenagers and comic book collectors. Parents would not want their children to be staring at screens as it may damage their developing vision. And comic book fans may want to collect physical copies of these books, even after reading them.

5.2.2 Number of Pages and Duration¶


These two features have the same relationship to the other features analyzed. Generally, higher number of pages also translate to longer reading time. As for the publication year, older books tend to have fewer number of pages/shorter reading time.

5.2.3 Number of Ratings and Text Reviews¶


These features are directly proportional to each other. More ratings usually translate to more text reviews as well. A higher count for both can be observed for those with more recent publication years and those with fewer pages/shorter reading time.

6. Conclusion and Recommendation¶

As a website, Goodreads.com has enabled its users and members to view friends’ bookshelves, share comments and provide ratings for each book available in the website. These ratings can provide an indication of the quality of a book.

The relationship of the different book features with the average book rating were analyzed through a series of aggregations and visualizations in order to determine the factors that influence a book rating. We found that the reading duration is not a significant predictor of book ratings. However, the number of book pages is directly proportional to book ratings. This is likely due to the generally long-story formats of acclaimed novels or epics and the engrossment of avid readers to the material. The same explanation would also make sense for the direct relationship between ratings count and book ratings, implying that readers are more inclined to submit a review for the books they like. Lastly, books which are more recently published have lesser variability in their ratings, signifying convergence to a universal ‘standard’.

Notable insights from the other features include the book format's effect on the reading time due to portability, and the preference of book format per genre, most evident in comics and children’s books.

One of the more obvious direct relations is between reading duration and the number of pages. There is also an apparent direct relation between the number of ratings and number of text reviews which can be attributed to an increase in engagement for extreme high or low ratings.

Our group advises authors to consider putting all their passion into writing their books and avoid thinking too much about the length of the book. The quality of books is increasing yearly and our group suggests writers to read more books so that their writing and ideas improve. Advertisers, and publishers can also leverage the insights on this analysis. Advertisers may actively encourage their readers to share their thoughts on the book in Goodreads. In a fairly similar consumer behavior in e-commerce, people tend to trust products with good ratings accompanied by sufficient text reviews.

In future study on Goodreads data, it would be interesting to look into user profiles like their age, gender, and other demographic and psychometric information of the reviewers.

The Goodreads data has further information that can be mined and analyzed. Possible next steps include performing machine learning algorithms to assess the expected rating of an author’s next book, possible book recommendation algorithms and other analyses.
